,"1471":"1471","1490":"1490","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1479":"1479","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","about 1440":"about 1440","1418":"1418","Sydmonton, Hampshire, England":"Sydmonton, Hampshire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England","England":"England","Barkham, Berkshire, England":"Barkham, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ingpen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Inkpen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inkpen","meanings":["English: locative name from Inkpen (Berks), which is recorded as  <i>Yngelpenne</i> in 1235–6."]}]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":37,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Amy Ingpen was born in 1418, in Barkham, Berkshire, England, her father, Richard Inkepenne, was 19 and her mother, Sarah, was 18. She married Richard Kingsmill I in 1435, in Barkham, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1479, in Sydmonton, Hampshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1418–1479":"1418–1479","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1415–1479":"1415–1479","1440–1511":